Title: Modeling Complex Flares With TESS 20-Second Data

PI: Tovar Mendoza, Guadalupe - University Of Washington

Type: SMALL

Summary: Stellar variability is a limiting factor for exoplanet characterization, especially around active M stars. Recent work has shown that given high enough resolution, flares show more signs of complexity. Many have modeled classical flares but less work has been done to model the morphology of complex flares. TESS 20-second data provides us with better resolution of short time scale variability which is smoothed out in the 2-minute data. We propose to use a sample of 5635 TESS 20-second light curves, combined with new stellar flare and starspot analysis methods, to model the morphology of complex flare events on active M stars. We will deliver 1. New publicly available tools to decompose complex flares and 2. The largest statistical analysis of complex flares with TESS 20-second data.
